USA: Repetition is the Mother of Wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest man, as a diligent student repeats in the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his eagerly awaited Afghan approach, it was shown to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only does the same text use the phrase “equal to Iraq” several times, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush’s January 2007 statement for his own statement: “A new path forward.”
He himself, who three years ago criticized Bush’s idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country that is suffering from the civil war, and that criticized him as “an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences.”
The following months, however, demonstrated that Bush’s strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so much so that nothing about Iraq is talked about today in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, but objectively left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than could be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama expects the miracle to happen again.
The field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal, who, despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected the undecided rifles in the White House to harsh criticism.
He called for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn’t think of anything better, so at least he tricked the general about 10,000 military.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic thing in Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years.The whole Obama doctrine generated more questions than the answers he offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq’s society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is fulfilled.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the head every day according to their needs.
The political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a Potemkin people, after which patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to the confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Not even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum goal of the whole operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama’s strategy shocks at his voluntarism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now about to explode.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "go home soon" will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will regard it as an indirect statement of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their voters, what the security of Germany or Italy has to do with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem by military force or not.
It will be necessary to seek answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left for the presidential election and therefore there is still a long time to find another strategy, if this is a total failure.
