The association UDF raises the tone and warns the New Center about the use of its acronym
The association UDF (Union for French Democracy), controlled by the MoDem (Democratic Movement) of François Bayrou, reacted on Friday to the attempt of the President of the New Centre, Hervé Morin, to launch an OPA (Public Procurement Offering) on the acronym of the former party of the Giscard d'Azur, under the guise of a demand.
Hervé Morin publicly announced his intention to regain the acronym UDF, considering that François Bayrou was not in a position to defend his political heritage after stretching out his hand to the left.
On the other hand, the Minister of Defense, whose party is associated with the UMP, had planned to confirm the strategy on Saturday before the National Council of the NC.
As a support to his management, he received the help of deputy Hervé de Charette (formerly UMP, present NC) who claimed ownership of the UDF brand, as he was the first to register it at the National Institute of Industrial Property in 2004.
But on Friday night, the office of the association UDF, controlled by friends of François Bayrou who do not want to be deprived of it, broke the silence to launch a request to the Minister and the MP by urging them to renounce the acronym and transfer the ownership rights of the brand, under penalty of lawsuit.
In recent days, you have made many statements insinuating that you would propose to your political movement to recover the acronym UDF, writes the association in a letter signed by 19 of the 24 members of the office, including François Bayrou and Marielle de Sarnez del MoDem, as well as Senator Jean Athuis of the Alliance Centrist.
They also believe it is correct to continue with the use of the name of the movement, the +Nouveau centre+, and the slogan +l'UDF d'aujourd'hui+ in its militant material and on the presentation page of its site, the signatories of the letter argue.
As you already know, they have no right to use the acronym, explains the UDF office that demands that the NC "immediately remove the mention of the name of the UDF from all media, as well as from (its) website".
He also asks Hervé de Charette "to transfer the ownership of (the) trademark to the legitimate rightholders".
Failure to do so will be appealed to justice to enforce the law and the legitimate rights of UDF members, the signatories warn.
In the letter, they specify that the UDF "is a real political movement since 1978" and recall that Morin and his friends "chose" to leave in 2007 "to create a new party, as others had already done in 2002 to create the UMP".
Therefore, the New Centre has, according to them, no right to use the acronym UDF.
They also recall that the last congress of the UDF voted in 2007 for its membership of the MoDem for three years and the creation of an office in charge of defending "the material and moral interests" of the movement founded by Valéry Giscard d'Estaing.
As for Hervé de Charette, the office continues, "when he registered the trademark", he was no longer a "member of the UDF for three years", but of the UMP.
It uses the absence of registration of the acronym UDF in a scandalous and fraudulent way to do it on its own.
This indiscretion is turning into crime, they denounce, before mocking the NC strategy: "We believe that in politics, as in life, it is more worthy to make your own name than to try to get out of anonymity by fraudulently taking a name to which you have no right".
Liliane Bettencourt: François-Marie Banier to be tried for abuse of weakness
On Friday, the Nanterre Court decided to sue the artist François-Marie Banier to determine whether, as billionaire Liliane Bettencourt’s daughter claims, she took advantage of the octogenarian’s state of weakness to rob her of a portion of her fortune.
The 62-year-old photographer, known for his photos of stars of the show, will be tried on April 15 and 16, 2010, for abuse of weakness, a crime whose conviction consists of a maximum sentence of three years in prison and a fine of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>375,000.
This means that in this case there will be a process worthy of a saga about one of the richest families in France, in which mother and daughter dispute the rules of the L'Oréal cosmetics empire.
But the Correctional Court No. 15 also ordered 87-year-old Liliane Bettencourt to undergo a medical examination by three medical professionals.
The heir and main shareholder of L'Oréal has always refused to undergo such examinations, even more so under the conditions proposed by the Prosecutor's Office of Nanterre during the investigation.
Physicians appointed on Friday will be required to submit a report by March 10, 2010, stating whether Liliane Bettencourt suffered from weakness and for what periods.
I think he'll take it.
“I’m going to talk to her,” Mrs. Bettencourt’s lawyer, Georges Kiejman, said as he left the hearing.
Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers’ lawyer, Olivier Metzner, was pleased with the court’s decision.
It is excellent news (...) The expertise will show that he (Banier) manipulated this older lady, whom we must protect, he said.
For the past two years, Liliane Bettencourt’s only daughter has initiated criminal proceedings against François-Marie Banier, a photographer and multifaceted artist, accusing him of taking advantage for years of his mother’s weakness to obtain <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 billion in donations, through checks, life insurance contracts or artwork.
For her part, Liliane Bettencourt has always denied being manipulated by the photographer, whom she considers a long-time friend.
On Friday, while the court was examining the origin of the action brought by Ms Bettencourt-Meyers, the lawyers’ allegations resulted, on some occasions, in a great family confession.
In this way, Liliane Bettencourt’s lawyer took into account three letters that her client sent to her notary (in 1999, 2003 and 2005) in which she said she distrusted Françoise Bettencourt-Meyers’ husband.
In the 2003 letter, Liliane Bettencourt added, according to the lawyer: "I could explain to my daughter that I wrote to Banier between once and twice a day for fifteen years.
Since her wedding, I have never been able to talk to Françoise again.”
The Nanterre Prosecutor’s Office once again considered that the plaintiff was not in a position to appear, especially since a guardianship judge had refused, in recent days, to give way to her request to open a judicial guardianship procedure for her mother.
Liliane Bettencourt "has full capacity to appear before the courts, is not under guardianship and has no guardian.
No one else will be able to appear in his place," said Prosecutor Marie-Chrsitine Daubigney.
Finally, the court decided that it would rule once the trial on the admissibility of Mrs Bettencourt-Meyers was conducted.
Management revolution or the end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of large French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain.
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is about employees adhering to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing on consumers products thought by factory technicians.
By placing the customer at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution gave way to market conquest strategies... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that have nothing to do with customer preference factors is repeated on a regular basis.
A demobilization of employees can end in deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all intellectual functions of the company, especially R&D and, even more, business intelligence.
Indeed, BI (Business Intelligence) "demands that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a forward-looking vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we called for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting employees at the center of the company’s concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have a relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did! B989
Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows in proportion to the importance of its own failures.
-Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great schools of engineers, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, for intellectual convenience, the ancient behaviorist theory that American “neurosciences” recently reactivated, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "commands" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent research by Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr reaffirms the managers in a mechanistic management position, unsuitable for today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the management revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, involves adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists in integrating in every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, engagement with the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to make reality part of their dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from Motifuncional Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
Studies have shown that they judge their company based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what the company offers them to achieve their own life projects.
By identifying and measuring mobilization factors, business managers can monitor, predict and anticipate their “social performance” and relocate human resources management “on the spot”.
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of a strong and effective business intelligence.
Oslo Speech: Obama Receives Right Praise for 'Just War'
On Friday, the U.S. right, satisfied that the 2009 Nobel Peace Prize had defended the concept of “just war” against U.S. enemies, hailed Obama’s speech on Thursday.
The Conservatives, who had discredited Obama’s Oct. 9 award, this time applauded the presidential speech, as did Sarah Palin, former vice presidential candidate during the 2008 election.
I loved what she said, Mrs Palin, a leading figure in the Republican party’s right wing, told USA Today, adding that she herself had addressed the issue of “sometimes necessary” war in her recently published memoirs.
In my opinion, war is, of course, the last thing Americans want to be forced to do, but it is necessary.
The terrorists must be stopped, he said.
Obama, who inherited the two wars of his predecessor George W. Bush in Iraq and Afghanistan, dedicated himself, on Thursday in Oslo, to justifying the use of force, a way to explain his decision to send 30,000 more soldiers to Afghanistan nine days earlier.
Another opponent of Obama, Newt Gingrich, considered that the president had done "a very good job" in Oslo.
I think the speech was really very good, the former Speaker of the House of Representatives rejoiced, who particularly appreciated the mention of "the existence of evil in the world" in the presidential words.
For a moment, the speech seemed very historic, Gingrich said, during an interview on the radio show "The Takeaway".
The former elected representative, whom some regard as a possible candidate for the Republican investiture for the 2012 presidential election, was pleased to hear "a leftist president" when he reminded Nobel Committee members "that they would not be free nor could deliver a peace prize if the use of force did not exist."
According to Michael Gerson, author of George W. Bush’s speeches and current Washington Post columnist, Obama delivered “a very American speech.”
In addition to presenting himself as a “citizen of the world,” as “always does,” he “talked like an American president” by reminding Europeans “that they live in a security bubble that they didn’t create and that they don’t do much to preserve it,” Gerson said.
Among the few not-so-convinced right-wingers, a Bush-era falcon, former U.N. ambassador John Bolton, called the speech "monotonous, pretentious and lacking in inspiration" on the National Review Online website.
On the left of the president, Democratic Representative Dennis Kucinich was alarmed to see Barack Obama justifying the use of force.
When we cover war with the notion of justice, it is easy to justify the massacre of innocents, he warned.
However, the center-left press praised the president.
Los Angeles Time, while still believing that Obama received the Nobel Prize prematurely, called his speech "superproduction" especially for a speaker known for his talent.
Oslo's speech "should serve as a roadmap to guide international decisions in the fight against conflict, poverty and oppression," the California newspaper said with enthusiasm.
Obama “pronounced the speech that was necessary,” the New York Times estimated, judging it “at the same time bleak and uplifting.”
Road Transport: Three Marathon Negotiations to Ensure Christmas Supply
After three sessions of marathon negotiations, the road trade unions and the TLF (Transport and Logistics of France), the only employers' organization that remained until the end, reached an agreement on Friday afternoon that puts an end to the strike slogan and the threat posed to Christmas supplies.
During the signing session on Friday night, Transportation Secretary Dominique Bussereau "rejoiced" about the deal, after several negotiating sessions that began on Wednesday morning.
After a second night of discussions, the negotiators bid farewell at dawn on Friday in the hope of quickly signing the text in accordance with the last hour of the morning.
Even when three employers’ organizations (FNTR, Unostra, OTRE) withdrew giving a break.
But a more than six-hour meeting that began at 11 a.m. was necessary for everyone to agree and the text to be signed at 6 p.m.
The conflict "would have been very damaging to businesses" and "would have been feared to disrupt the holidays," Bussereau said.
The text foresees an increase of 4% for the lowest wages (in local and regional road transport), and of 2.9% for the highest (international transport).
The hourly rate rises from 8.72 euros to 9.06 for low wages.
It's not much, but we started with a lot of disadvantage, Patrice Clos (FO) explained.
If so, we will give the order to our militants that there will be no more cuts or blockades in the supply centers.
But there can always be some dissatisfied rebel, he added.
Philippe Grillot, president of the TLF, acknowledged that this is a "good deal", although it was "difficult to grant increases to high wages given international competition".
According to him, the increases will be on the order of 170 euros per month for low wages and 100 to 120 euros for the highest.
It is a common sense agreement that respects wage earners, Maxime Dumont (CFDT) said, while Thierry Douine (CFTC) recognized it as "a historic agreement".
For Richard Jaubert (CGT) it is "an acceptable commitment".
The agreement also foresees an increase in travel costs of 3% and the holding of general assemblies for road transport in the first half of 2010, which will mainly address the issue of an extraordinary salary and a modernization of the collective agreement.
Bussereau recalled that “a <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>100 million drop in employers’ fees” was the subject of a government amendment to the 2009 amending finance bill, which the National Assembly voted on Thursday night.
The government will ask the Senate to vote “under the same terms.”
The signing of TLF allows the agreement to be applied, firstly, to the companies affiliated to this organization and, secondly, to the whole profession, in the event that the Minister of Labour makes an extension.
It will be done “with the utmost urgency,” Bussereau said.
The opposition of employers’ organizations could only delay the process.
The FNTR denounced it as a “naive business”, as the 100 million euros “had already been promised to the sector to offset part of the CO2 tax”.
The Secretary of State for Transport forced us to negotiate in an emergency situation, not as a conclusion to an analysis discussed by the parties, but not to discourage those who wish to eat turkey at the next Christmas dinner, Unostra lamented.
For the OTRE, the agreement puts "the stability of many SMEs in the sector over the next 12 months" at risk.
RER A: conflicts during the weekend, unions dissatisfied with the proposals of the RATP
Conflicts in the RER A, France’s largest public transport line, will continue over the weekend, because at Friday’s meeting, the 2nd day of strike between trade unions and the management of the RATP, there was no agreement and the unions were dissatisfied with their premium request.
For this important Christmas shopping weekend, on Saturday and Sunday only trains will run between 10 a.m. and 8 p.m., due to one train in two on the central section (between La Défense and Nation) and one train in four on the other lines.
Interconnection with the SNFC will be suspended in Nanterre Prefecture, forcing passengers to change trains.
The Lafayette Galleries, which expect 200,000 customers every day, were delighted that "RATP is striving to provide service to the big stores."
The RER A crosses from West to East the Parisian city.
The RATP route runs from Saint-Germain-en-Laye and Nanterre to Boissy-Saint-Léger and Marne-La-Vallée.
This Friday, roughly one in two trains ran in peak hours, and almost no trains in valley hours, as had been anticipated.
On Thursday there was no unrest in the Andes thanks to the organization of the inhabitants of the Isle of France.
In this way, at dawn, the station of Saint-Germain-en-Laye (Yvelines) was much less crowded than usual, mainly due to the absence of students.
In Boissy-Saint-Léger (Val-de-Marne), Jack Nbakina, a 29-year-old engineer, explained that he had got up "an hour and a half earlier to get on schedule".
The Saint-Lazare station was not saturated, the SNCF said, which had planned the supervision of police and law enforcement.
The RER A operated by the SNCF from or to Cergy-Le-Haut arrived or departed from Saint-Lazare station to join the subways.
New general assemblies of workers on strike will take place on Saturday and Sunday. The results, "unsatisfactory" according to the unions, will be analyzed from a meeting held with the management on Friday afternoon.
The Director of RER proposes to negotiate a specific protocol in all aspects for RER A: working time, professional development, etc.
That’s not what drivers want when they claim a premium they owe, according to Thierry Garon (South).
The RATP even puts its premium proposals between parentheses, the CGT commented outraged, noting that the management "was not able to solve a problem that the SNCF and the road sector had already solved".
A new meeting is planned on Monday to carry out "a more extensive analysis on the conditions of the exercise of the profession," the RATP said.
This also prompted unions to say that the company “didn’t care about the weekend users.”
In the morning, about 150 drivers invaded a committee at the headquarters, in Paris.
Then the management, which until then refused to dialogue during the strike, suggested the meeting "to calm the waters".
The conflict could extend to RER B on Tuesday, after UNSA and the Independents have filed a pre-warning.
The unions ask for a premium of 120 euros (Unsa) to 150 euros, of which 30 euros are variable (CGT, FO, CFDT, Sud, Indépendants) and complain about the degradation of working conditions on this line that has one million passengers daily.
RER drivers, all in the second grade of their professional career, charge from 2,200 to 2,700 euros gross and from 600 to 650 euros of premiums, for schedules with alternate shifts, Sundays and holidays.
Turkish Justice Dissolves Pro-Kurdish Party, A Decision With Serious Consequences
The Turkish Constitutional Court ruled Friday in favour of the dissolution of the country’s main pro-Kurdish party, a decision that immediately provoked anger in the Kurdish community, in the southeast of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision could greatly complicate the task of the government, which has just given a helping hand to the Kurdish community trying to put an end to 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society (DTP) party was dissolved because it had become the "focus of activities that undermined the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Court President Hasim Kiliç told reporters after four days of deliberations.
The decision of the 11 judges was unanimous, although only a seven-vote majority was needed to achieve the dissolution, Kiliç said, adding that 37 of the party's leaders, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysel Tugluk, were separated from political life for five years.
The judge also announced the end of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Türk and Tugluk, and the confiscation of the party's assets by the Treasury.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 550).
Its leaders warned before the verdict that deputies would leave parliament before being unbiased parliamentarians.
The decision follows a procedure launched by Supreme Court prosecutor Abdurrahman Yalçinkaya in 2007, accusing the DTP of obeying the "principles" of the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK), considered a terrorist organization by Ankara and many other countries.
Numerous observers believe that the DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
However, the party says it has no “organic ties” with the PKK, but refuses to classify it as a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court’s verdict comes as the government lends a hand to the Kurdish community by proposing a series of measures to strengthen their rights so that the Kurds stop supporting the PKK and end the conflict.
The DTP leaders said a dissolution could generate an escalation of tensions in Southeastern Anatolia, where a large number of demonstrations against the detention conditions of PKK leader Abdullah <0xC3><0x96>calan have degenerated into clashes with police over the past few weeks.
Since the announcement of justice, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP premises in Diyarbakir, the major city in the southeast, mostly populated by Kurds.
Law enforcement fired tear gas grenades and used water cannons, while demonstrators threw Molotov bombs or stones with spears.
In Istanbul, about a hundred people were also concentrated.
After the verdict, Türk said the justice decision was going to "deepen discouragement".
Turkey cannot solve this issue (Kurdish, NDLR) by dissolving a party, he told the press.
The government, made up of a party from the Islamist movement, also regrets the decision.
In principle, we oppose the closure of parties.
This is not going to solve anything, Energy Minister Taner Yildiz said.
This decision completely boycotts the democratic openness launched by the government, commented political analyst Ahmet Insel.
We can expect, of course, a reaction from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed an attack in which seven soldiers were killed three days earlier in northern Turkey, one of the bloodiest attacks in recent months.
Snow can start suddenly.
A truly cool winter is what Wolfgang Brauburger wants.
It is absolutely something with which you want to make life impossible for citizens, says the director of road maintenance in the winter of the ESF
But with this, your employees can learn to test and master the entirety of vehicle technology.
On the weekend, meteorologists may announce it for the first time.
More than 330 employees and 120 vehicles are ready to take care of snow and ice.
In this case, the EDF acts in accordance with a detailed plan.
As soon as it snows heavily in Frankfurt and temperatures fall below zero degrees, 20 of the so-called A stretches with large vehicles with salt come out, Brauburger explains.
These include, for example, the main arteries and avenues such as the Neue Weg and the Hanauer Landstraße.
But also accesses for firefighters, public transport routes, pedestrian areas and sloped sections, such as the Atzelbergstraße.
ESF service starts around 3 a.m.
Approximately 1,040 kilometers should be covered, as needed, in a maximum of three hours with wet salt, which sticks better.
That is why the ESF starts around three o'clock in the morning, "with this the tracks are free until the traffic of the peak hours begins".
The hard part is when it starts snowing around 7:30 a.m.
"Then we have a problem," says the director of road maintenance in winter, "because then no one is ready to clear space for salted vehicles."
Immediately afterwards, when it is no longer snowing, it reaches the secondary and private roads, to which the Rat-Beil-Straße also belongs.
The last priority is the side and secondary streets.
That’s where the inconvenience is generated, Brauburger knows well.
Around five o'clock in the morning, the ESF infantry are launched, the dangerous points and cruise ships are mainly cleared.
In general, the ESF could not take over all bicycle lanes.
In Frankfurt there is a special service, which does not lose sight mainly of the bridges, says Brauburger.
As these become slippery quickly, the vehicle with salt starts as soon as the temperature drops below two degrees.
In case of an emergency, the police can also call them.
The Cradle of the Dinosaur
The Tawa hallae had the same appearance as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran over the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with claws in the shape of a shovel and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, it would not have been something special.
But the Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these bodily characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday’s journal Science.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at that time was in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window towards the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico in 2006.
Sometimes, we have found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is something unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis, a team member at the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation, the remains of five specimens were collected in total.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an exceptional finding: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not entirely share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says for example Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods, among which are the Tyrannosaurus Rex, the Velociraptor and also the birds, the quadruped sauropods known as the "long-necked" sauropods, the Stecenus per hernivorius and their relatives.
According to the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in Tawa’s skull, researchers found hints of airbags, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae also the bones of the spine were evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive airbag theropod, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related lineage of later giant sauropods also possessed air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves migrating to North America
Because the earliest dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers deduce that the saurians first appeared there.
Accordingly, the three genealogical lineages separated at first and spread from South America to all corners of the Earth, which at that time still formed a single terrestrial mass, the supercontinent Pangea.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
The three cannot descend from a single related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe that at least three waves migrated to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are opponents as well.
An even older species, Silesaurus, belonging to a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
Their view could give a distorted picture, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils are still preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to Mesozoic dominant terrestrial vertebrates remains an enigma.
While in the Triassic, dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of current crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread around the world and many new species developed, while the kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary to the Jurassic.
Success stories were not eternal.
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction to which the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halted the rise of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then had a miserable existence: mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
The list is long and the international signatories.
Participate professors from the University of Toronto, Cambridge, Vienna or Berkeley, California.
Teachers from Naples, Quebec, Edinburgh, New York, Sao Paulo, Berlin or Bremen participate.
The police eviction of the occupied casino from the Goethe University in Frankfurt had an impact worldwide.
278 professors and professors from Goethe University, although also from higher education centers across Germany, Europe and North and South America, stand in solidarity with protesting students at the Westend Campus.
In a statement written in German and English, they "reject" the police eviction promoted by the board of directors.
Werner Müller-Estler, president of the university, evicted the building occupied by students and teachers on an educational strike last week because the walls and works of art were covered with propaganda.
As a result, five students were injured.
The material damage, the signatories judge, does not justify "the violent dissolution of the courses organized by the same students and faculty by a police command".
The eviction represented an "unacceptable attack" on freedom of research and learning.
The exclusive focus on vandalism served to "de-legitimize and criminalize the protest" and diverted attention from the content.
The Governing Council has refused to enter into the necessary negotiations.
Teachers demand the immediate withdrawal of the judicial claim.
Most occupants have not caused any material damage, it is said.
Legitimate protest
The youth of the Verdi union and the German Federation of Trade Unions also stand in solidarity with the students.
The protest is the legitimate expression of a growing concern for the future itself, says Verdi national youth secretary Alexander Klein.
Eva Kühne-Hörmann (CDU), Minister of Science of Hesse, however, defended the performance of the university’s rector and the police.
We are grateful to the Rector of the University.
Destruction and occupation are totally unacceptable means, he said in an issue of Aktuelle Stunde on Thursday in the parliament of the province of Wiesbaden.
We are sympathetic to the protest, but we are not sympathetic to vandalism,” said Peter Beuth, CDU’s provincial parliamentary delegate.
The opinion of the opposition factions, the SPD, the Greens and the left, is different.
The CDU used painted walls as a pretext to criminalize the protest, Janine Wissler (Left) said.
Instead of thoroughly studying the students’ arguments and demands, they are evicted.
The Left has submitted a motion requesting the Minister of the Interior to submit a report on police intervention.
New Silicon Valley
For many years, it was considered a secret city, inaccessible to Western visitors.
Selenogrado, one of the ten districts of Moscow, was in the Soviet Union a heavily guarded site for secret weapons research.
Today, the community of 216,000 inhabitants, located 37 kilometers from the center of Moscow, is considered the "Russian Silicon Valley".
Here are important research and production centers of micro and nanoelectronics.
Since September 2008, representatives of Selenograd have contacted the Riedberg Scientific Headquarters in Frankfurt, university institutes and the companies of the Frankfurt Innovation Center (FIZ).
Several mutual visits were made and now, on Wednesday, Selenograd and Riedberg sign a "close collaboration protocol" in Frankfurt.
Deputy Mayor of Moscow Yuri Rosljak and the Mayor of Selengrad, Anatoly Smirnov, headed the Russian delegation; for Frankfurt signed the head of planning services Edwin Schwarz.
In 2010 representatives of the FIZ and directors of small and medium-sized enterprises of the Natural Sciences Research Centre will travel to a seminar in Selenograd.
Scientific exchanges
This is a continuous scientific exchange.
