Oniric worlds
In a waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only in the case of mentally ill and drug addicts that the boundaries between imagination and reality fade.
As long as it happens during sleep, everything is in order.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can unhinderedly surrender to the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during waking hours, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered in the modern Western world to be a madman or a drug addict, or at least a maniac.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in drug addicts.
The fault lies in our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint paintings or write novels, sometimes cause the boundaries between sleep, madness and reality to be undone.
Onirically modified states of alert consciousness can appear in the most diverse forms, at best we call them visions, and at worst, madness.
Although the triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to the visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, the psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions arise when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain – especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine – has been derailed and the interaction between various parts of the brain is disrupted.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and insane thoughts often occur.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and physicians since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived hallucinations as a form of sleep in a waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, observed in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness with the oniric states", for Sigmund Freud, the dream was even "a psychosis, with all the unpurposed, alouds and forms".
It is the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book figure.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over him, it is floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of demons with wings, with red muzzles like blood, deformed, shaking teeth.
They're chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pain all over his body.
Striking and evil voices resonate from the walls and the radio.
He can no longer bear them, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls two cables from the stereo, ties them together to form a hanging knot, and attaches them to a hook on the ceiling.
He climbs into a horn and puts the knot around his neck.
Jump.
The rope is loose.
What a lesson to you!, shout the voices in a chorus that blows his tympanics, "Go to the clinic and have them cure you!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychoses, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, he is also manic-depressive, takes medications, against depression, mania, schizophrenia.
He has learned to live with his illness, he has been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality
Approximately one percent of the population falls ill at least once in the life of schizophrenia; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common disease after depression.
In an acute schizophrenic psychosis, most of the time those affected can no longer distinguish between the outside and the inside world, and fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, disorders in the relationship, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The affected person is no longer able to distinguish what is important from what is not, the brain can no longer filter the disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the doors to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered on the subject, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician at the General Psychiatry Clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed to him.
At the same time it enters a passive role, as in a dream, it feels overwhelmed by events and cannot actively organize them.
This is why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled, and manipulated.
In general, it is not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in a lifetime
Unlike in a dream, Fuchs says, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality perceived in psychosis remains in principle as it is."
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the distancing from experience takes place in reality.
For researchers still an unknown why our brain makes cabriolets.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can cause anyone to temporarily lose contact with reality.
But not all people develop a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic disposition for schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that in addition to genes, there are also other determining factors.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it is still unknown how this alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which is also not manifested at all for many years.
The influence of the environment also plays an important role – stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers of a psychosis when a previous disposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis, as they interfere with the brain’s transmitting system.
When the brain heats up
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer with their hallucinations and take very expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says Lübeck psychology professor Erich Kasten.
Perceiving a hallucination as pleasant or not often depends on the point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die unreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our heads), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical accompanying symptoms of psychoses, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
Among them are, alongside mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depressions, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer’s and cranial trauma.
surprisingly and under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also suffer hallucinations.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are composed of memories that are normally suppressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain in which sensory perceptions are processed are hyperactive or little restricted; when our brain warms up, but also when stimuli are lacking.
Drugs can cause this condition in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also the restriction of stimuli, stress, the evil of love or other brain states of exception.
In recent studies, up to a third of respondents reported having experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Vorpommern and attending a secondary school.
An ordinary girl.
If it weren't for those images and voices.
Sometimes, during recreation, it happens that a clumsy guy with long, dark hair directs the word to him.
When she answers, the other students look at her astonished; no one, apart from her, hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a bit strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she’s not dreaming.
She is awake and she sees and hears that boy, just as she sees and hears the girl sitting on the bench next door.
You may even feel their presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, he likes the guy.
Sometimes she wonders if she's crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he is in class, sometimes he cannot follow the lesson because the teacher – in his eyes and ears – is introducing a new companion, while for the rest he explains the mathematical equations in a visible and audible way.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for sleep, which often comes late and is scarce, he does not know how to distinguish whether he is awake or dreaming, whether the images he sees, the muzzles or the girl with bleeding cuts in his arms and legs, appear in front of his eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he yells at the figures.
She hasn't told her parents and friends anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is today20 years old.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations have been gone for a year.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten over the Internet, she knows she’s not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art by despair.
According to Kasten, when a person finds himself socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while he will begin to have hallucinations.
I think the brain is unemployed and is in charge of looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., her only daughter, was a little scared of the other kids and often played alone.
His hallucinations began when, at the age of 13, he learned that the man he has been calling Dad since he has been using reason is not his biological father.
Since visual and acoustic hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and noises, those affected, such as Sarah K., find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality.
Hallucinations are equally images that the brain produces, which is why they seem so real.”
Kasten also classifies night fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people do not differ fundamentally from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that her patients appreciate her hallucinations as a special skill.
Limit situation between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences usually pathologize, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor in Heidelberg and chief physician at the clinic for psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative – madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated the so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Oniric hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that can not subsequently distinguish from being awake.
Onyrical conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while being fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of self or of the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, this replaces a very dangerous real situation with a self-conscious and imaginary world that is decoupled from reality.
A form of boundary situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an insurmountable situation in itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen of Zurich also describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as an action to save the soul.
He was 49 years old, when his conscience embarked on several days of travel after an operation of the heart valves with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility in the intensive care station.
Claussen plunged into a world created by him and visited strange places from other times: he was found lying in bed, an elderly man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watched over his health.
It was seen in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle abducted him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the Alps with snow firn and met a Korean mobster.
He gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, memories of mental journeys are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intense even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our daily experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and narcotic use show how fragile the inner reproduction of the outer reality is, even when we are awake.
Each modification of the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a deformation of what we call reality."
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
