75% of working mothers have had work problems due to their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of the younger generation who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Women's fertility and work trajectory in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt about this: 75 per cent of working mothers have seen limited employment opportunities due to motherhood.
The study notes that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation in couples and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they develop.
Those who do not have an out-of-home activity, work part-time, or have an unstable job, begin cohabitation earlier, advance first motherhood, and have more children.
In contrast, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer descendants.
“Women between 35 and 49 years old with fixed jobs have their first child, on average 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time from their life trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and arrival of their children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on maternity, albeit less on the mating schedule," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when getting married and having the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at which they marry and at which they have the first child.
The difference is also maintained between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those with elementary and higher education were mothers for the first time at an average of 25.1 and 32.1, respectively.
"A further division between women is established according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before they get a stable job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and prioritize getting a stable job as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child,” Delgado says.
